when we connect with two container monog and nongo express we will get an interective view after http://localhost:8081/ - user: admin and pass: pass

*******************************************************
how to run it
********************************************************
Use these commands from Command Prompt in order.

Open the project folder
cd /d D:\React\DockerProject\student-registration-app
Start MongoDB containers
docker compose -f backend\mongodb.yaml up -d
Check that containers are running
docker compose -f backend\mongodb.yaml ps
Verify MongoDB authentication
docker exec backend-mongo-1 mongosh -u admin -p admin --authenticationDatabase admin --eval "db.runCommand({ connectionStatus: 1 })"
Start the backend
cd backend
node server.js
If you want to stop the containers later
docker compose -f backend\mongodb.yaml down


***********************************************
FROM node

ENV MONGO_dB_USERNAME=admin
ENV MONGO_dB_PASSWORD=admin

RUN mkdir -p backend
COPY . /backend
CMD ["node", "/backend/server.js"]

**********************************************************

1. FROM node

This tells Docker:

"Start building my image using the official Node.js image."

Think of it like installing an operating system with Node.js already installed.

The official Node image already contains:

Linux OS
Node.js
npm (Node Package Manager)

So instead of installing Node manually, Docker downloads this image.

For example:
Base Image
--------------------------------------------------
Ubuntu/Linux
Node.js
npm
--------------------------------------------------
Your application will be built on top of this image.
--------------------------------------------------
ENV MONGO_dB_USERNAME=admin
ENV MONGO_dB_PASSWORD=admin


2. ENV

This creates environment variables inside the container.

These are similar to Java's:

System.getenv("MONGO_DB_USERNAME");

or in Node.js:

process.env.MONGO_dB_USERNAME
process.env.MONGO_dB_PASSWORD

After this line, inside the container:

MONGO_dB_USERNAME = admin
MONGO_dB_PASSWORD = admin

Your server can read them like:

const username = process.env.MONGO_dB_USERNAME;
const password = process.env.MONGO_dB_PASSWORD;

Instead of hardcoding:

const username = "admin";

Environment variables are preferred because credentials can be changed without modifying code.

--------------------------------------------------

RUN mkdir -p backend

3. RUN

RUN executes a Linux command while the image is being built.

Here Docker runs:

mkdir -p backend

which means:

Create a folder named backend.

The -p option means:

If it already exists → don't show an error.
If parent folders don't exist → create them too.

Equivalent in Windows:

mkdir backend

After this step:

/
backend/

exists inside the image.

COPY . /backend
--------------------------------------------------
4. COPY
This copies files from your local machine into the Docker image.

Suppose your project is:

Backend
│
├── server.js
├── package.json
├── package-lock.json
└── routes

Docker copies everything:

COPY . /backend

Result inside the image:

/
backend
    server.js
    package.json
    package-lock.json
    routes

. means:

Current folder.

/backend means:

Destination inside the Docker image.

---------------------------------------------------
CMD ["node", "/backend/server.js"]

5. CMD

This tells Docker:

When the container starts, execute this command.

Equivalent command:

node /backend/server.js

which starts your Express server.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------
---------------------------------------------------
What happens when you run docker build?
---------------------------------------------------
Imagine your Dockerfile is read from top to bottom.

Step 1

Docker downloads:

Node Image

↓

Step 2

Adds environment variables

USERNAME=admin
PASSWORD=admin

↓

Step 3

Creates folder

/backend

↓

Step 4

Copies your project

server.js
package.json
routes

↓

Step 5

Saves everything as a new Docker image.

Nothing runs yet.
---------------------------------------------------
What happens when you run docker run?
---------------------------------------------------
Now Docker creates a container from the image.

Docker Image
       ↓
Docker Container

Then it executes:

node /backend/server.js

Your Node server starts.
---------------------------------------------------
Image vs Container
---------------------------------------------------
Think of it like this:

Image = Recipe

Ingredients
Instructions

It cannot execute anything by itself.

Container = Cooked food

You create it from the recipe.

Image
   ↓
Container

You can have:

1 Image

↓

Container 1
Container 2
Container 3

Many containers can be created from the same image.
---------------------------------------------------
One important improvement
---------------------------------------------------
Your Dockerfile works, but it is not ideal because it doesn't install your project's dependencies (node_modules).

A more typical Dockerfile looks like this:

FROM node

WORKDIR /backend

COPY package*.json ./

RUN npm install

COPY . .

ENV MONGO_DB_USERNAME=admin
ENV MONGO_DB_PASSWORD=admin

CMD ["node", "server.js"]

Why this is better:

WORKDIR sets /backend as the working directory, so you don't need full paths.
COPY package*.json and RUN npm install install your dependencies inside the image.
COPY . . copies the rest of your application after dependencies are installed, which also improves Docker build caching.
The environment variable names use the more conventional MONGO_DB_* format (your original names with MONGO_dB_* still work as long as your code uses the same names).

Once you understand this flow—Dockerfile → Image → Container → Node process—most Docker concepts become much easier to grasp.